{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958051601/0267.xml":{"full_text":"Reuther Says GM Attempts\nTo \u2018Goad\u2019 Union Into Strike\nAuto Workers Pres. Walter\nP. Reuther has charged Gen\neral Motors with trying to\ngoad the union into a strike\nby its unprecedented tactics\nin announcing termination of the\npresent contract as of May 29\u2014\ntwo days before the union\u2019s con\n.9 tracts with Ford and Chrysler\nexpire.\nThe UAW, said Reuther, is not\ngoing to \u201caccommodate\u201d them\nwith a strike that would merely\nhelp the industry to sell its in\nOli\nWRITES\nBy KENNETH KOCH\nFinancial Secretary,\nLocal 11-346\nOil, Chemical Atomic Workers\nThe merger convention which\nwas held in Cleveland last week\nwelded together 1,000,000 mem\nbers of the labor, movement into\none organization in Ohio. This is\nthe largest central body of all\nthe 36 states which have merged\nso far.\nIt is the duty of all members\nt\nChampion\nIV\nSparklets\n\nBy RALPH YOUNG\nUnion Office:\nThere will be a Special Unit\nmeeting on Sunday, May 18 at\nLocal 12 Parlor B at 2 p.m. for\nthe purpose of nominating a\nsecretary of the Unit. Please at\ntend and nominate the person\nof your choice.\nCongratulations to Mr. and\nMrs. Al Koszyckieon their 23rd\nwedding anniversary on April\n23. Al works in Department L,\n1st shift. Best of luck to both\nof you for the future.\nSales tax stamps from: Joe\nSleja, EE 1st; Mabel McDowell,\nD 1st; Joe Griner, A 2nd, and\nMargaret Harding, laid off.\nThanks from the children of the\nI\nSummer Camp.\nColonel Tarver E 1st:\nMildred Grove wishes to thank\nher friends for all they have\ndone for her during her illness.\nGeorge Cunningham is men\ntioned this week because he is\nalways willing to help his fel\nlow-workers, when he has a\nspare moment.\nMarcella Malinowski made\nher friends at Champion happy\nwhen she returned to work this\nweek after an absence of sev\neral weeks, due to illness.\nFay Pulley wishes to thank\nher many friends for their sym\npathy during her bereavement\nfollowing the death of her\ngrandson.\nCharles Kazalia thanks his\nfriends for the many kindnesses\nthey have shown him during his\ncurrent illness.\nUnion Office:\nSorry to see that Mike Posad\nny, Dept.' G/ls still off work due\nto illness. His wife sent a note\nof thanks to the fellows in G\nfor visiting him. Good luck,\nMike.\nThanks to Frederick Reining,\nlaid off, for the first \u201cbuck\u201d to\nthe COPi-brive. Fred sent in a\ncheck on Monday morning.\nSave. Electric\nBy HAZEL ELGIN\nWe have-more trouble with\nthe personnel, manager working\nupstairs. Twice this last week\nshe was seen working and told\nabout it. If management doesn\u2019t\ndo something- soon, we'll have\nto do something ourselves. It\u2019s\nunfair to use every excuse, to\ncall an emergency, to service a\nunit.\nWe also have trouble with\nraising production on the units\nand inserting machines.\nWe have always kept the units\ngoing all day. All of a sudden,\nwe cannot.\nI have talked with some of\nthe operators and they say that\nthe units have been speeded up.\nThat would make us seem slow\ner.\nOn some of the inserting\nmachines, the rates the company\nasks just cannot be made. Even\nif they could, the winders\ncouldn\u2019t do the work. Produc\ntion rates are not supposed to be\nraised, unless there is a change\nin methods, material, or equip\nment.\nWell, we have more pleasant\nthings to talk about. Mary Hus\ntig became engaged two weeks\nago. Her boyfriend\u2019s name is\nJohn Kubricsek. She'had a brid\nal shower last week. She was\nmarried last Saturday, May 10th.\nStella Tomar had a birthday\nMay 15. Happy birthday, Stella.\nhd:\n411\nLate birthday, Edith Shaffer,\nMay 5th.\nA very happy Soother\u2019s Day\nto all the mothers and grand\nmothers.\nOur chairlady, C aroline Wood\nlord, was chosen to go to Cleve\nland on the AFL-CIO merger.\nWe are very honored that one\nof our people was chosen out of\nquite a few from Toledo.\nt\nventories of 850,000 new cars.\nThe termination notice fol\nlowed on the heels of a rejec\ntion by the big three automobile\nmanufacturers of a UAW propos\nal designed to insure labor peace\nand restore prosperity to the in\ndustry.\nThe possibility that the Big\nThree auto makers were\nworking in close cooperation\nin negotiations was raised by\nreports that General Motors,\nFord and Chrysler had held\ni conferences among their top\nof the Union to work together\nand show good will toward each\nother and strive to make this or\nganization as effective as it\nshould be and can be. The ene\nmies of labor are united and la\nbor surely must be united to pro\ntect the interests of all its mem\nbers as well as the interests of\nall the people of our nation.\nOur delegation from Local\n11-346 was impressed by the\nhigh type of leadership that was\ndisplayed at the convention.\nUAW President Walter P. Reu\nther had a stirring message for\nall the delegates. I could not\nhelp thinking how good it would\nbe if all the members could hear\nhis message.\nCharles Romine who is presi\ndent of his Local Union at Wav\nerly, Ohio, was elected by the\nOCAW delegates at the conven\ntion to serve as a vice-president\nand executive board member of\nthe Ohio AFL-CIO. Jurisdiction\nmatters which are the biggest\nbone of contention between most\nsegments of the merged Unions\nwill be ironed out at the top\nlevel of the AFL-CIO and will\nnot be acted upon by the Ohio\nAFL-CIO.\nThe Ladies Auxiliary Local\n11-346A will hold a card party\non May 17, 1958, (this Saturday)\nat 8:00 p.m. at the Union Hall at\n2910 Consaul St. There will be\ndoor prizes, a raffle, and lunch\nwill be served. Be sure to attend.\nPrice is $1 per person.\nWe are happy to hear that\nSteve Lintner is on the mend\nafter his recent mishap and wish\nhim a speedy recovery.\nContinental Jet News\nBy LOU ELIAS\nMay 18, this coming Sunday,\nis our regular Unit meeting.\nNominations of candidates for\nofficers of your Executive Com\nmittee will be part of the agenda.\nIt can\u2019t be emphasized strongly\nenough how important it is for\nevery Unit member to be there.\nDon\u2019t be content to be specta\ntors. You are to select and sup\nport your leaders who will rep\nresent you for the next two\nyears. Don\u2019t make this coming\nelection a popularity contest but\nsupport only those candidates\nwho are capable and will work\nfor your welfare.\nWe express our deepest sym\npathy to Stanley Swierczek,\nDept. 3S1, whose mother passed\naway last week.\nZigmund Bonkowski, Dept.\n351, entered the hospital for sur\ngery last week. We wish you\nluck and a speedy recovery. We\nare glad to see Don Hall, Dept.\n300, back with us. He had a brief\nstay at the hospital.\nLast week, Wednesday, Ernie\nFoley, Dept. 308, celebrated his\nbirthday. We wish to say, \u201cHap-\npy Birthday,. Ernie.\u201d Wouldn\u2019t\nit have been nice to remember\nyour birthday with a day-off\npaid-holiday? Something to\n1\nthink about, eh?\nThe C.A.E. Marathon bowling\nleague concluded their season\nlast Friday with a fun night. The\nleague champions, Cutter Grind,\nwere honored with very nice\nbowling trophies. Dewey Wyre\nbaugh, John Ayers and yours\ntruly were also honored with,\nspecial achievement award tro\nphies.\nThe champion Cutter Grind\nteam is composed of Cliff Harri\nson (Capt.), Bob Mohr, Lester\nVan Fleet, Ron Balsly and Dick\nCoveney. They finished like\nchampions by beating a good\nFinal Inspection team for three\ngames and four points on the\nfinal night of the season to put\nthem on top by one point. Final\nInspection led the leaguep rac\ntically all season long. Tough\nluck boys but better luck next\nseason. Cliff Harrison couldn\u2019t\nf\ncMon\"\nTroUP\nTDeen\u2019s\nmosnesom\"\"\nB\"stor\u00ae\njeffertO\"\neft 19101\n112\ni\nlevel bargainers. One confer\nence was Mid to have In\nvolved GM and Ford negotia\ntors. Chrysler, reportedly rep\nresented in similar meetings,\nrefused to confirm or deny it.\nFlatly rejecting the UAW\nproposal to extend the con\ntracts into September, the auto\nmanufacturers countered with\na request for a .two-year ex\ntension of the expiring con\ntracts without alteration. On\nthe heels of this proposal came\nGM\u2019s notification to the union\nof contract termination.\nUAW Vice Pres. Leonard\nWoodcock, director of the union\u2019s\nGeneral Motors Dept., termed\nthe GM action \u201ca signal it hopes\nto force industrial strife,\u201d but\nsaid the UAW would not be\n1 \u201cmaneuvered into a strike, par\nticularly at a time handpicked\nby the corporation.\u201d\nHe called\nthe\ncompany\u2019s ma\nneuver a \u201cthreat to industrial:\npeace\u201d in an effort to win a tac-\ntical advantage at the bargaining,\ntable. He declared General Mo\ntors could \u201cbest serve the na\ntion\u201d by reducing prices of its\n44a\nproducts and \u201cending its pri\nvate repeal of the law of sup\nply and demand.\u201d\nIn testimony before the House\nBanking C o m m i ttee, Reuther\npointed to the stockpile of new\ncars in dealers\u2019 and manufac\nturers stocks and predicted\n\u2018further layoffs\u201d by the auto\nmobile industry to deplete these\ninventories.\nOn the Surface At\nSurface Combustion\nBy \"WHY WORRY\"\nWell, we got back from the\nconvention OK.\nNot much news. Things have\npicked up in the Fabrication\nDept. Put up bids for 3 fitters, 4\nwelders and 1 burner.\nCarl Pawlik is in the hospital;\nhad an operation, hope he has a\nspeedy recovery.\nRoy and John got their boats\nin the water, but very little\nwater.\nBob\nAdams\nwanted\nto\ncome\nhome Thursday night because his\nyacht was put in.\nj The Convention went along\nI good.\nBut whatever you do vote\nagainst the Right-To-Work law.\nI Thanks to Jess Miller and his\nI wife for the Sales Tax Stamps.\nhave waited for a better time to\nshoot a very creditable 636 ser\nies. His superb bowling achieve\nment led his team to victory\nand the league championship.\nCongratulations Cliff and to\nyour Cutter Grind team.\n(Remember Sunday, May 18.)\nAmerican Floor\nSweepings\nBy NORM WITHERELL\nThe election of our Unit of\nficers will be held in the plant\nlunch room on May 27th be\ntween the hours of 7:00 to 7:30\na.m., 12:00 to 12:30 noon, and\n4:00 to 4:30 p.m. The candidates\nfor the various offices are as\nfollows: Chairman, Roman Ry\nwalski and Ralph Jones; Vice\nChairman, Terrance Kerwin;\nSecretary, Frances Schlagheck\nand Donna Craig; Committee\nman-at-Large, Velma Cangiamil\nla, Paul Viola, Milo Vogt, Paul\nKornowa, Robert \u201cBob\u201d Linden\nmuth, Thomas \u201cTom\u201d Crabtree,\nKay Gryca and Bernard \u201cBer\nnie\u201d Pemberton. Let\u2019s have a\nclean fight. Keep your chin\ndown and your punches up and,\nas they say\u2014\u201cMay the best man\nwin\u201d.\nThanks to Madelyn Dickson\nfor her collection of Sales Tax\nStamps. I also want to thank the\nothers of you who have put\nstamps in the boxes for same.\nThese stamps are used to send\nneedy children to the Local 12\nSummer Camp at Sand Lake,\nMichigan. This camp, always\nrated one of the best in the\n(country, has been improved and\nis even better than ever. New\nand larger living quarters and\nother facilities have been added\nto take care of an increasing\nnumber of children. Summer\ncamp time is almost here. If you\nare planning on sending your\nchildren, or if you know of any\none else who wants to send\ntheirs you had better get your\napplications in as soon as pos\nsible. The rates are as follows:\nchildren of Local 12 members,\n$10.00; non-members, $15.00\nWe are glad to welcome back\nto work Allan \"Al\u201d Henderson\nafter four months rest due to a\nCoronary condition. Al is going\nto be in charge of the lunch\nroom for the time being. Take it\neasy Al and the best of luck.\nWe are sorry to hear that Ray\nmond \u201cRay\u201d Hankinson is back\nin the hospital and we hope he\nhas a speedy and complete re\ncovery this time.\nDelia \u201cDee\u201d Davis is recover\ning from another siege in the\nhospital.\nv\nJOINT ACTION TO FIGHI social health hazards has been\npledged by the American Social Hygiene Association and AFL-CIO\nCommunity Service Activities in a 10-point memorandum of un\nderstanding. Shown signing the document are (left to right) Philip\nR. Mather, ASHA president; Conrad Van Hyning, the association\u2019s\nexecutive director, and Leo Perlis, director of Community Service\nActivities for the AFL-CIO.\nSpicer Views and News\nBy FRANK GOLEMBIEWSKI\nI have been contacted again by\nquite a few of our members who\nhave been examined at the\nWillys Diagnostic Clinic. They\nare all well satisfied with the\nexamination and the nominal\ncost, but their question to me has\ni been: \u201cWhy aren\u2019t we in the\nCity-Wide Charity Fund? If we\nwere in it, it would be an addi\ntional 20 per cent savings to\nthem.\nI can only answer them by\nsaying that a small minority of\nthe regular membership were a\nmajority at the Union meeting\nand voted it down.\nThey then ask me why as in\ndividuals they are not allowed to\nJoin the Charity Fund as indi\nviduals. I can only say that we\nhaven\u2019t approached anyone to\nstart a campaign for individual\nmembers.\nI think it is a very good idea,\nthough, and I will see if it can't\n1\nbe expanded to let all who want\nto join to sign up. Then if we can\nget enough signed up we may\neven be able to get the company\nto take this idea, with the under\nstanding that those signed up for\nthe City-Wide Charity Fund will\nnot be pestered with collections\nof any kind in the plant.\nMembers also should have a\npin or plastic pocket holder to\ndistinguish them from others\nwho do not belong.\nAlthough work isn\u2019t picking\nup at Spicers as yet, prospects\nfor the future look encouraging.\nWe'll just have to wait it out.\nStandard Printing Co.\nBOOK JOB PRINTING\nWedding Announcements, Ete.\n520 Jackson CH 3-1705\nAuto-Lite\nMemo\nBy CLARICE ZIEMAN\nThe May 17 meeting will be\nvery important because the elec- i\ntion committee will be nomi-l\nnated and elected among those\npresent. It is suggested that our\nunemployed people attend and\nperhaps be elected to serve on\nthe election committee, and have i\na chance to earn some you\nknow-what.\nThere will be nominations of\nofficers for the Auto-Lite Execu-.\ntive Committee plus delegates\nto the Inter-Corp. Council.\nIf you have any clothes, shoes,1\nor furniture that you would like\nto give to the Local 12 Summer\nCamp Women's Guild for their\nrummage sale. May 22 and 23,\nplease bring them to the office\nor call Ch. 1-9128 for pickup\nservice.\nWe would like to express\nour deepest sympathies to\nHelen Schults, Dept 118, and\nJulia Schell, Dept 428, who\nlost their mother, Mrs. Meri\nPapp, and to the family of\nEvelyn Irvin, Dept 408, form\nerly of Dept. 118. Evelyn\nworked at Auto-Lite 21 years\nand suffered a fatal heart at\ntack last Saturday.\nWe want to send get well\nwishes to Edith (Peg) Roberts,\ncommitteewoman, who is in\nRoom 255, Flower Hospital, and\nto Erba Butler, Dept. 428, who is\nin Mercy Hospital.\nWedding bells will ring out\nMay 24 for Julia Szalkay, former'\nA. L. inspector and Carroll\nKeuhle, steward in Dept. 1.\ni\nThanks, Danny Silverthorne,\nDept. 112, for the cigar box full I\nof tax stamps for the Summer\nCamp. Leave a few cigars in\nthe box next time as Theresa is I\ntrying to break the cigarette\nhabit.\nI\nThe seniority dates as of\nMonday, May 12 are: Men\u2014\nOctober 28, 1936; Women\nJanuary 17, 1935.\nor BECKMAI OPTICAL CO.\nEstablished ISIS\nd Oldest Optical Company\nIn Tolada\nK MINUS. OPTOMETRIST\nPhon* CH. 3-5512\n203 Edward Lamb Bldg.\n1\nI\nBuilding Trades to Weigh\nMeany Job Disputes Bid\nAFL-CIO Pres. George Meany has urged the Building\nand Construction Trades Dept, to \u201cgo along with partial im\nplementation\u201d of a plan to resolve jurisdictional disputes.\nAt the same time he proposed continuing explorations\nto resolve a problem posed by the Steelworkers, who claim\n11. _2 2s a\nthat past practice in certain\nareas of the country makes it\ndifficult for the union to rati\nfy the disputes plan.\nThe question came before the\nAFL-CIO Executive Council\nwhen representatives of the\nBuilding and Construction\nTrade* Dept, presented a state\nment calling for all union* af\nfiliated with the building trade*\nand the IUD to be bound by the\nagreement worked out by Meany\nand a special council subcom\nmittee last February.\nThe building trades claimed\nthat the Steelworkers\u2019 refusal\nto ratify the agreement cast\ndoubt on the entire plan to 1\nsettle jurisdictional disputes, i\nThey told Meany they would\ncarefully consider his request.\nMeany told a press conference\nthat the issue involved was new\nconstruction on steel properties.\nThe USWA in some areas have\nbeen involved in new construc\ntion\u2014an area given to the build\ning trade* under the disputes\nplan\u2014for more than 20 years.\nIn one case in Portsmouth. O.,\nbuilding tradesmen are working\non the same job.\nUSWA Practices Cited\nThe Steelworkers, said Meany,\nbelieve that this past practice\nshould not be upset and there\nfore have not ratified the plan.\nHe urged that the trade*\ncontinue \u201cpartial implementa\ntion\u2019\u2019 while attempts continue\nto resolve the Steelworkers\u2019\nproblem. He said that while\nabout 36 percent of the dis\nputes involve the USWA,\nmany others had been settled\nunder the agreement.\nDefined Jurisdictions i\nThe February agreement set\nout area* of jurisdiction giving\nnew construction to the building\ntrade* and general production\nand running maintenance to the\nindustrial union*.\nIn the doubtful areas between\nthese two, decisions would be\n1\nmade on the basis of established\npast practice in a plant, area\nor industry basis.\nAyling\nReichert\nBy MARY WYATT\nPress Dept.:\nA farewell party was given on\nMay 2nd for Fred Welty, who\nretired recently. The gang pre\nsented him with a clock-radio,\nwhich we hope will fill in a lit\ntle of his leisure tme.\nFred, who has been with A.\nR. since May 8, 1933, was a\nvery faithful and conscientious\nworker all those years. He cele\nbrated his 69th birthday on Nov,\n26 of last year. He and his wife,\nMartha, also celebrated 46 years\nof wedded bliss March 23 of this\nyear. In closing, we want to\nwish Fred the best of luck with\nmany years of continued happi\nness with his wife in their Cam\nden St. home.\nA speedy recovery to Mary\nHanson, in Flower Hospital,\nwhere she underwent surgery\nrecently.\nAssembly Room:\nHere is the list of nominees\nfor our coming election, to take\nplace on Wednesday, May 21 in\nParlor B at 7:30 p.m.:\nChairman, Mary Myers; sec\nretary, Mary Baker and Mary\nWyatt; Committee, Katherine\nLehman, Clarence Macklin,\nBlanche Oswalt, Denzil Sheck\nler and John Stager.\nIt is important to attend this\nmeeting, whether you are work\ning or laid off, so you can vote\nfor your favorite candidate. The\ncommittee elected will serve you\nfor the next two years.\nAlice Neipp and family spent\nMother\u2019s Day with her daughter\nand family in Wadsworth, Ohio.\nt\n1938\u2014Blue Cross 20th Anniversary\u20141958\n\"Sure makes it easy\nthe way Blue Cross pays\nthe Hospital direct\nno claims to file.\"\nt\nI\nk\nNo waiting, no red tape, no claims\u2014you go home from the hospital with\na secure feeling because Blue Cross pays the hospital direct for the serv\nices you receive. And you can keep your Blue Cross regardless of age,\nwhen you retire, or are laid off.\nGet the best in services and added benefits with Blue Cross\nBlue Cross, preferred by 56 million persons, 435,000 in\nnorthwestern Ohio, provides many outstanding and exclu\nsive features for its subscribers.\nFULL COST OF SERVICES: Blue Cross provides the hos\npital services needed at no\ncost to the subscriber depend\ning on the terms of the contract under which the preson\nis covered.\nRETIRED? LAID OFF? When a subscriber retires or is laid\noff, his Blue Cross protection continues as\nlong as he pays\ni\nl\n\nthe premiums applicable to the contract written for Direct\nPay subscribers.\nEQUAL FAMILY BENEFITS: Each member of the sub\nscriber's family is entitled to the same benefits provided\nfamily contract. Approximately 75% of the\nthrough a\nbenefits paid by Blue Cross are\nand children.\nfor the employee's wife\nYou can enroll in Blue Cross today\nIf you are under 65, in good health,\nself employed,\nworking where fewer than 10 persons are\nemployed.\nmcROs^\nIf you are working where 5 or more\npersons are employed, consult your\nemployer about forming a group.\nENROLL TODAY AT\nThe Hospital Service Association\nof Toledo\nHelps Pay\nHospital Bills\nd\n2139 Madison\n508 Third\n201 N. Park\n404 Feick Bldg.\nToledo 2\nDefiance\nFremont\nSandusky\n1\n1\na\nWORLD-WIDE BENEFITS: Blue Cross provides protection\nwherever you are hospitalized. The Inter-Plan Bank is th*\nnational clearing house for thousands of hospital cases each\nday at home or abroad.\nNO RED TAPE: No credit references, claims or red tap*\nhamper a Blue Cross subseriber when he needs hospital\ncare. Presentation of the Blue Cross identification card is\nall the hospital requires.\nCHILD PROTECTION: Dependent children who reach the\nage of 19 are eligible to continue their Blue Cross protec\ntion.\n9\nLOW COST: Blue Cross operates on\na low-cost basis. Th*\nPlan is non-brofit, pays no commissions and board mem\nbers donate their services. Approximately 95 cents out of\nevery $I received is paid out for subscriber's hospital care.\nOR MAIL THIS COUPON\nThe Hospital Service Association of Toledo\nJ\n2139 Miditon Ave. Toledo 2, Ohio\nPlease send me without obligation, information about my eligibility\nfor enrollment in northwestern Ohio's Blue Cross plan.\nName\nAge\nAddress\nSelf-employed\nEmployed whirl fewer thin 5 are working\nName et Cempeny\nwhere I work\nNo. of\nEmployees\nt\nName of (Husband) or (Wifi)\nAjtn.HWMW\nEmployed by\nNo. 